# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: snowflake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] A **cloud database** is a database that typically runs on a cloud computing platform, with access provided as a service.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] There are two common deployment models: users can run databases on the cloud independently, using a virtual machine image, or they can purchase access to a database service maintained by a cloud database provider.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Cloud databases may use either a relational SQL or a NoSQL data model.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Database services handle scalability and high availability, while making the underlying software stack transparent to users.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Cloud platforms allow users to purchase virtual machine instances for a limited time, on which a database can be run.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Users can upload their own machine image with a database installed or use ready-made machine images that include an optimized installation of a database.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] With a database as a service (DBaaS) model, users pay a cloud provider for database services and computing resources, which may reduce the operational overhead needed to develop and manage databases.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Users are provided with tools to create and manage database instances, as well as to manage database users.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Some cloud providers also offer tools for managing database structures and data.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] The design and development of typical systems often use data management and relational databases as key building blocks.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Advanced queries expressed in SQL work well with the strict relationships imposed by relational databases.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] However, relational database technology was not originally designed for use over distributed systems.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] This limitation has been addressed through clustering enhancements, although some fundamental operations—such as data synchronization—still require complex and expensive protocols.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Modern relational databases can exhibit poor performance on data-intensive systems.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] As a result, the NoSQL paradigm has been adopted within database management systems for cloud-based systems.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] NoSQL storage does not require fixed table schemas, and join operations are typically avoided.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] NoSQL databases have been shown to provide efficient horizontal scalability, high performance, and ease of integration into cloud applications.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Additionally, data models that rely on simplified relay algorithms have been employed in data-intensive cloud mapping applications specific to virtual frameworks.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] It is also important to differentiate between cloud databases which are relational (SQL) and those that are non-relational (NoSQL).
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] SQL databases can run in the cloud either on virtual machines or as a managed service, depending on the vendor.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] While SQL databases are generally easy to scale vertically, horizontal scalability presents a greater challenge.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] making them well suited to cloud environments.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] However, many contemporary applications are built around a relational (SQL) data model, so adopting NoSQL databases often requires significant changes to application code.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] or similar variants), and key-value store data types.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Multi-model databases combine relational and non-relational capabilities, providing a standard SQL interface to users and applications.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] Native multi-model databases support multiple data models with a single core, facilitating their use in applications built around SQL.
[src:snowflake/cloud-database] The following table lists notable database vendors that offer cloud database services, classified by deployment model—machine image or database as a service—and by data model (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:snowflake/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:snowflake/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake is powered by an advanced data platform that is provided to you as a self-managed service.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake’s data platform brings together data storage, processing, and analytic solutions that are faster, easier to use, and far more flexible than traditional offerings.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake combines a completely new SQL query engine with an innovative architecture that is natively designed for the cloud.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] It offers full enterprise analytic database functionality, and unique features and capabilities.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake uses public cloud infrastructure to host virtual compute instances and persistent data storage.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake manages software updates and infrastructure so you don’t have to.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can’t install and run Snowflake locally or on private cloud infrastructures, whether on-premises or hosted.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake’s architecture is a hybrid of traditional shared-disk and shared-nothing database architectures.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Similar to shared-disk architectures, Snowflake uses a central data repository for persisted data that is accessible from all compute nodes in the platform.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] But similar to shared-nothing architectures, Snowflake processes queries using massively parallel processing (MPP) compute clusters, where each node in the cluster stores a portion of the entire data set locally.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] When data is loaded into a Snowflake table, Snowflake reorganizes that data into its internally optimized, compressed, columnar format.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake stores this optimized data in cloud storage.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake tables are ideal for data warehouses.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake manages all aspects of how this data is stored — including the organization, file size, structure, compression, metadata, and statistics.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] All data in Snowflake tables is automatically divided into *micro-partitions*, which are contiguous units of storage.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Micro-partitions improve efficiency and provide other benefits.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can use Snowflake tables to store structured and semi-structured data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can also use the FILE data type for unstructured data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information about Snowflake tables, see Understanding Snowflake Table Structures.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Apache Iceberg™ tables for Snowflake combine the performance and query semantics of typical Snowflake tables with external cloud storage that you manage.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] They are ideal for existing data lakes and data lakehouses that you can’t, or choose not to, store in Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Iceberg tables store their data and metadata files in an external cloud storage location; for example, Amazon S3, Google Cloud Storage, or Microsoft Azure Storage.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] The external storage isn’t part of Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can use Iceberg tables to store structured and semi-structured data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Apache Iceberg™ tables.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Hybrid tables are optimized for low latency and high throughput by using index-based random reads and writes.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Hybrid tables support row locking and enforce unique and referential integrity constraints, which are critical for transactional workloads.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can use a hybrid table along with other Snowflake tables and features for Unistore workloads that bring transactional and analytical data together in a single platform.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] You can use hybrid tables to store structured and semi-structured data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Hybrid tables.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] A *virtual warehouse* is a cluster of compute resources in Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Virtual warehouses process SQL statements and, using Snowpark, run code in languages, such as Java, Python, and Scala.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] With Snowpark Connect for Spark, you can also run Apache Spark™ workloads on virtual warehouses.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Each virtual warehouse is an independent compute cluster that doesn’t share compute resources with other virtual warehouses.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] As a result, each virtual warehouse has no effect on the performance of other virtual warehouses.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Virtual warehouses.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] The cloud services layer is a collection of services that coordinate activities across Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] These services tie together all of the different components of Snowflake in order to process user requests, from sign-in to query dispatch.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] The cloud services layer also runs on compute instances that are provisioned by Snowflake from the cloud provider.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Instead of moving data to different systems so that different teams can complete specific operations and tasks, you can bring all of your workloads directly to their data with an integrated set of features.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake separates storage and compute, which simplifies some traditional challenges of data engineering, such as infrastructure management and performance tuning.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Data engineers can focus on implementing pipelines that ingest, transform, and deliver data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] In addition, SnowConvert AI can ingest and transform data, and Snowpark Migration Accelerator can convert code from various platforms to Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Overview of data loading.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] With Snowflake, you can scale workloads dynamically based on demand, access different types of data — including structured, semi-structured, and unstructured — and share data easily.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] These features let you analyze data stored in Snowflake to extract meaningful insights, patterns, and trends for analytical use cases, such as business intelligence or predictive modeling.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake simplifies the use of artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) capabilities so you can perform AI and ML feature engineering, training, and inference with your Snowflake data.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Models can access your most up-to-date data in a secure environment.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] With Snowflake, you can avoid the cost and complexity of moving your data to a separate platform for AI and ML tasks.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Snowflake AI and ML.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowflake offers many ways to build applications and share them with your teams, partners, and customers.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] When you use Snowflake to share data, you control access to the data, and avoid the challenges of keeping it synchronized in different places.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] Snowgrid is Snowflake’s cross-region, cross-cloud technology layer.
[src:snowflake/intro-key-concepts] For more information, see Sign in to Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake Inc. was founded in July 2012 in San Mateo, California, by Benoît Dageville, Thierry Cruanes, and Marcin Żukowski.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Dageville and Cruanes previously worked as data architects at Oracle Corporation; Żukowski was a co-founder of Vectorwise.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Mike Speiser, a venture capitalist at Sutter Hill Ventures, which provided early funding to the company, served as its first CEO.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In June 2014, Bob Muglia, formerly of Microsoft, was named CEO.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In October 2014, Snowflake came out of stealth mode; at that time, it was used by 80 organizations.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake has run on Amazon Web Services since 2014, on Microsoft Azure since 2018, and on the Google Cloud Platform since 2019.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In June 2015, Snowflake launched its first product, its cloud data warehouse.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In May 2019, Frank Slootman, formerly CEO of ServiceNow, joined Snowflake as its CEO.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In June 2019, the company launched Snowflake Data Exchange.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In December 2020, the company added Knoema as a data provider in the Snowflake Data Marketplace.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In May 2021, the company became a distributed company, with a principal executive office in Bozeman, Montana.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] On February 28, 2024, Frank Slootman retired as CEO and was replaced by Neeva's cofounder Sridhar Ramaswamy.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In February 2026, Snowflake reported Q4 fiscal 2026 product revenue of $1.23 billion, up 30% year-over-year, with full-year product revenue reaching $4.72 billion.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Remaining performance obligations totaled $9.77 billion, a 42% increase, reflecting strong demand for AI infrastructure.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] The company reported over 9,100 accounts using Snowflake AI features.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake develops and sells a cloud-based data platform known as the Data Cloud.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] The platform allows organizations to unify data warehousing, data lakes, data engineering, and data sharing into a single service.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake runs on public cloud infrastructure such as Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud Platform (GCP), and separates compute from storage for scalable, on-demand analytics.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2020, Snowflake introduced Snowpark, a developer framework that enables writing data pipelines and business logic using Java, Scala, and Python directly within Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2021, Snowflake launched Unistore, a hybrid workload that combines transactional and analytical operations within the same platform, enabling real-time applications to be built directly on Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2023, the company introduced the Native App Framework, which allows developers to build, distribute, and monetize applications that run securely within a customer’s Snowflake account.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake also provides services including Snowpipe for continuous data ingestion and the Snowflake Marketplace, where organizations can access and share live, query-ready datasets.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2024, Snowflake launched Cortex, a set of generative AI services embedded into the platform.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Cortex includes access to large language models, vector search, and model deployment capabilities, allowing users to build AI-powered applications using SQL or Python.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Recently, it has introduced Snowflake Intelligence.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Snowflake supports workloads such as machine learning, streaming analytics, business intelligence, and unstructured data processing, with integrations for tools like Tableau, Power BI, and Sigma Computing.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In October 2022, the company acquired a 5% stake in advanced TV advertising firm OpenAP.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In May 2023, Snowflake agreed to acquire privacy-focused search startup, Neeva, for $185 million.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In June 2025, Snowflake announced its acquisition of Crunchy Data, a provider of cloud-based PostgreSQL services and distributor of certified Postgres, for approximately $250 million.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Later that year, Snowflake relocated its headquarters back to California, in Menlo Park.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In January 2026, Snowflake announced an agreement to acquire Observe, an AI-powered observability company.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2024, hundreds of customers of Snowflake were targeted as part of a mass customer data theft and extortion campaign by the ShinyHunters hacking group.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Data breaches affected Ticketmaster, Advance Auto Parts, Santander Bank, Neiman Marcus, LendingTree, AT&T, Pure Storage, and Bausch Health.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In May 2024, Snowflake collaborated with Mandiant in an investigation which found no evidence of Snowflake’s environment being breached but rather customer credentials being compromised.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Two men were involved in the hacking conspiracy that were a part of the ShinyHunters hacking group.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Connor Riley Moucka aka Waifu/Catist, 25, of Kitchener, Ontario, and John Erin Binns aka IRDev.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] Moucka was arrested on October 30, 2024; a Washington state court has issued an indictment on charges of conspiracy, computer fraud and abuse, extortion, and aggravated identity theft.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In 2012, Snowflake raised $5 million in a Series A round.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In June 2015, the company raised $45 million.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In January 2018, the company raised $263 million at a $1.5 billion valuation, making it a unicorn.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] In October of that same year, the company raised $450 million in a round led by Sequoia Capital, at a $3.5 billion valuation.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] On February 7, 2020, the company raised $479 million.
[src:snowflake/snowflake-inc] The company went public in September via an initial public offering, raising $3.4 billion in one of the largest software IPOs and the largest to double on its first day of trading.
[src:snowflake/tables-micro-partitions] All data in Snowflake is stored in database tables, logically structured as collections of columns and rows.
[src:snowflake/tables-micro-partitions] To best utilize Snowflake tables, particularly large tables, it is helpful to have an understanding of the physical structure behind the logical structure.
[src:snowflake/tables-micro-partitions] These topics describe *micro-partitions* and *data clustering*, two of the principal concepts utilized in Snowflake physical table structures.
[src:snowflake/tables-micro-partitions] They also provide guidance for explicitly defining *clustering keys* for very large tables (in the multi-terabyte range) to help optimize table maintenance and query performance.
[src:snowflake/user-guide-intro] Overview of getting an account and methods for accessing Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/user-guide-intro] Overview of the different ways to connect to Snowflake.
[src:snowflake/user-guide-intro] Description of Snowflake architecture, key concepts, and features.
[src:snowflake/user-guide-intro] Overview of Snowsight, Snowflake’s web-based interface.
[src:snowflake/user-guide-intro] Introduces the main operations and corresponding SQL commands for getting your data into Snowflake and then using it to perform queries and other SQL operations.
